## Repo profile
*Only this block varies per repo; everything below it is identical across all repos.*
- Smoke/build: no test suite (Python CLI). Offline smoke: `.venv/bin/python -m py_compile cs/*.py` (parse) + `.venv/bin/python -m cs --help` (CLI wiring) — both exit 0 with no engine. Semantic check = a read-only live verb against the engine: `.venv/bin/python -m cs whoami` / `cs plan` / `cs dossier <email>`. Never claim "works" without a real verb run.
- Static docs (on demand): `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` (as-built — **source of truth**; wins over `CLAUDE.md` and this file; read first), `docs/general-operator-plan.md` (original handoff/history), `docs/drafts-rpc-plan.md`, `docs/case-study-centralix-vonage-cutover.md`. Absolute constraints: `CLAUDE.md` §5 "Safety (NEVER)" + outreach policy in the support@ profile `USER_NOTES` (engine-side, edited via `cs rpc settings.update`, never in this repo). NB `CLAUDE.md` is partly stale vs. code (see alignment check 1) — verify against `cs/` before trusting an absolute.
- Active-context: `docs/active-context.md` (primary — carries `doc_baseline_commit`).
- Execution plans: `docs/execution-plans/` (none yet — create on first plan).
- Routing: single tree ⇒ everything → `docs/active-context.md`.
- Repo-specific alignment checks: (1) **Send boundary** (code-verified 2026-06-30): the headless/cron operator NEVER sends — verbs are read-only/draft-only and sends are double-denied by the cron wrapper `cs/scripts/cs_operator_cron.sh --disallowed-tools` AND `.claude/settings.json` (`cs chat`, `cs rpc chat`, `campaign send-draft`, `rpc settings.update`). Sending needs a deliberate human `CS_TRIAGE_MODE=send` + relaxed perms. Two real send surfaces must stay behind that gate: contextual replies → the engine's approval-gated `send_draft` (`cs chat --allow send_draft`); fixed-template bulk → **cs-owned SMTP** (`cs/send_mail.py`, also driving the *excluded* `migration_loop`). `CLAUDE.md` §5/v2 "no cs-owned SMTP" is overstated — code has one by design (matches §2/§6 + the hb ownership map). (2) Identity ALWAYS support@; the `CS_ACCOUNTS` registry holds only `@mrcall.ai` uids — never an `@cafe124.it` uid (that is the separate `124-cs` project). (3) Outreach style/policy lives in the engine profile's `USER_NOTES` (`cs rpc settings.update`), NEVER as ad-hoc style files or per-prompt coaching in this repo. (4) Relevance/triage classification of free text = LLM with structured output, never regex/string matching. (5) RPC response wrapper keys are not uniform (`threads` vs `emails` vs bare array) — parse the documented key (`CLAUDE.md` §1) or silently get 0 rows (every caller `.get(key, [])`-degrades to `[]`). (6) Dedup truth = Gmail's Sent folder (`cs contacted` / `cs/gmail_archive.py`), not the engine archive.
- Notes: private GitHub `hahnbanach/mrcall-cs`, branch `main`; runs on `desktop.mrcall.ai` (cron opt-in; Phase 1 draft-first; `dry_run=True`/`autonomous=False` defaults). Built to be **cloned** for other companies — `124-cs` (`~/124`) is the sibling clone; keep the two strictly separate. Never auto-commit; the operator reviews.

Load project knowledge: durable layer on demand, volatile state up front. Pull the smallest high-signal set into context — not everything.

## Already in context — do NOT re-read
Project + user `CLAUDE.md` are auto-loaded at session start; re-reading them wastes context. Verify the project `CLAUDE.md` is still a thin index (pointers, not prose) — flag it if it has grown into a full document. Monorepos: nested `CLAUDE.md` files not on the root path (see profile) are NOT auto-loaded — read those.

## Phase 1 — Durable layer (read on demand)
These rarely change; do not bulk-load them. Run `ls ./docs/` to map the knowledge base, then open a static doc (see profile) only when the task enters its area. Absolute constraints (system-rules / "Core Rules") are the exception — know them before touching code.

## Phase 2 — Volatile layer (read now)
1. Read the active-context file(s) in the profile — last done / in progress / next. The primary one's frontmatter carries `doc_baseline_commit`.
2. Doc drift: `git rev-list --count <doc_baseline_commit>..HEAD` = commits landed since docs were last synced. (Absent ⇒ baseline not established yet; note it.)
3. List active plans in the execution-plans dir (see profile) whose `status` is not `completed`.

Working tree + recent commits (pre-injected):
!`git status --short`
!`git log --oneline -n 8`

## Phase 3 — Constraint smoke check (conditional)
The smoke command (see profile) guards code work — it is NOT a session-start blocker. Skip it when only orienting, or on a clean, in-sync tree; don't pay a multi-minute build to read docs. Run it before modifying code and surface any pre-existing breakage.

## Output
No summaries or greetings. One line:
`Context loaded. [N] docs indexed. Baseline <sha> (<N> commits behind HEAD). [active plans / violations]. Ready to work.`
